-- Japan, South Korea, Philippines, Taiwan: Asian Bonds and Currency Preview
-- B y   F r a n c e s   Y o o n
-- 2010-10-06T23:26:18Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-06/japan-philippines-south-korea-taiwan-asia-bonds-and-currency-preview.html
The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in Asia’s local bonds and
currencies today. Yields and exchange rates are from the
previous trading session unless stated otherwise.  Japan: Chief Cabinet Secretary  Yoshito Sengoku  will hold
media briefings at 11 a.m. and 4 p.m. in Tokyo.  The Ministry of Finance will release at 8:50 a.m. in Tokyo
its report on the nation’s official reserve assets for
September.  The Cabinet Office will release at 2 p.m. in Tokyo its
report on Japan’s broadest leading indicator of economic health
in August. The leading index, a composite of 12 indicators
including inventories and machine orders, fell to 99.1 in August
from 100.0 in July, according to a Bloomberg News survey of
economists.  The Ministry of Finance will announce at 10:30 a.m. in
Tokyo the amount of 30-year Japanese government bonds it plans
to sell on Oct. 14.  The yield on the 1 percent government bond due September
2020 was at 0.84 percent, according to Japan Bond Trading Co.,
the nation’s largest interdealer debt broker.  The yen traded at 83.02 per dollar at 8:19 a.m. in Tokyo.  Philippines: The Philippines central bank is expected to
keep its overnight borrowing rate at a record-low 4.0 percent
today for an 11th straight month, according to economists
surveyed by Bloomberg.  The central bank will announce foreign reserves data for
September. In August, it held $49.91 billion in reserves.  The yield on the 6.125 percent debt due September 2020 was
6.08 percent, according to Philippine Dealing & Exchange Corp.
The peso was at 43.882 per dollar.  South Korea: The Bank of Korea will release the country’s
September bank lending figures to households. Lending amounted
to 420.3 trillion won ($377 billion) in August.  The yield on the 3.75 percent security due in June 2013 was
3.3 percent. The won traded at 1,115.35.  Taiwan: The Ministry of Finance may say export growth was
unchanged for a second month at 26.6 percent in September,
according to the median estimate of economists surveyed by
Bloomberg. Imports are forecast to have increased 30 percent
last month, compared with 28 percent in August.  The yield on the 1.125 percent note due in September 2020
was 1.18 percent. The Taiwan dollar was at NT$31.132 per dollar.  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Frances Yoon in Seoul at   fyoon2@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Sandy Hendry at   shendry@bloomberg.net  